
[1]astrolabe

   AS'TROLABE, n. [Gr. a star, and to take.]

   1. An instrument formerly used for taking the altitude of the sun or
   stars at sea.

   2. A stereographic projection of the sphere, either upon the plane of
   the equator, the eye being supposed to be in the pole of the world; or
   upon the plane of the meridian, the eye being in the point of
   intersection of the equinoctial and the horizon.

   3. Among the ancients, the same as the modern armillary sphere.
